## Context

`src/builtins/edit.rs` implements an atomic-rename write pattern inline:

```rust
let mut tmp_path = resolved.clone().into_os_string();
tmp_path.push(".tmp");
let tmp_path = PathBuf::from(tmp_path);

if let Err(e) = tokio::fs::write(&tmp_path, new_content.as_bytes()).await {
    return Err(err(EditError::IoError { reason: format!("write tmp: {e}") }));
}
if let Err(e) = tokio::fs::rename(&tmp_path, &resolved).await {
    return Err(err(EditError::IoError { reason: format!("rename: {e}") }));
}
```

ARCHITECTURE.md describes this as the "atomic-rename pattern" that "ensures Edit never leaves a partial write on disk." The Write tool (next in the inter-phase) has the same correctness requirement: a partial write on disk is just as bad for Write as for Edit. Insert may need it too (it rewrites the file after splicing).

Currently 1 consumer; promotion is justified by 1-2 imminent additional consumers and the safety-critical nature of the pattern (silent divergence between Edit's and Write's atomicity story would be a real bug).

## Goal

Extract the atomic write+rename to a shared crate-private helper BEFORE the Write tool lands, so Write consumes the same well-tested helper and we avoid two slightly-different copies of the same atomicity-critical code.

