## New types in `src/model.rs`

```rust
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub struct ModelInput {
    pub turns: Vec<Turn>,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub struct Turn {
    pub role: Role,
    pub content: Vec<ContentPart>,
}

#[derive(Clone, Copy, Debug, PartialEq, Eq, Hash)]
pub enum Role {
    System,
    User,
    Assistant,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub enum ContentPart {
    Text(String),
}
```

Notes:
- `ContentPart` is non-exhaustive in spirit (Phase 2 will add `ToolUse`, `ToolResult`). Mark it `#[non_exhaustive]` so external matchers cannot become brittle. Phase 1 has exactly one variant.
- `Turn.content` is a `Vec<ContentPart>` even though Phase 1 only ever produces a one-element Vec containing `Text(...)`. The Vec is the future-proofing seam; one allocation per turn is acceptable.
- `Role` is `Copy` (it's a 3-variant unit-only enum). `ModelInput`, `Turn`, `ContentPart` are NOT `Copy`; they contain owned strings.

## New `ARModel` trait surface

```rust
pub trait ARModel: Send + Sync {
    fn complete<'a>(
        &'a self,
        input: &'a ModelInput,
    ) -> std::pin::Pin<Box<dyn futures::Stream<Item = Result<ModelStreamEvent, Error>> + Send + 'a>>;
}
```

The `system_prompt: &str` parameter is REMOVED. The system text is now part of `input.turns` as `Role::System` turn(s). The `messages: &[Block]` parameter is REMOVED. The Model never sees a `Block`.

`DLModel`, `ModelStreamEvent`, `Usage`, `ModelRole`, `model::Error` are all UNCHANGED.

## Agent changes in `src/agent.rs`

The current event loop calls `let context = self.history.linearize(); ... model.complete(&self.system_prompt, &context);`. Replace with inline construction of `ModelInput`:

```rust
let mut turns: Vec<Turn> = Vec::with_capacity(self.history_len_estimate() + 1);
turns.push(Turn {
    role: Role::System,
    content: vec![ContentPart::Text(self.system_prompt.clone())],
});
for block in self.history.linearize() {
    match block {
        Block::UserMessage { content, .. } => turns.push(Turn {
            role: Role::User,
            content: vec![ContentPart::Text(content)],
        }),
        Block::AgentMessage { content, .. } => turns.push(Turn {
            role: Role::Assistant,
            content: vec![ContentPart::Text(content)],
        }),
        Block::ReasoningTrace { .. }
        | Block::ToolCall { .. }
        | Block::ToolResult { .. } => {
            // Phase 1: these variants are kept in History but not routed to the model.
            // Phase 2 (tool calls) will route them via ContentPart::ToolUse/ToolResult.
        }
    }
}
let input = ModelInput { turns };
let mut stream = model.complete(&input);
```

Replace `self.history_len_estimate()` with `self.history.linearize().len()` if no convenient capacity estimator exists; capacity is a hint, not correctness, so prefer the cheap obvious thing. If `linearize` already allocates a `Vec<Block>`, an alternative is to iterate once and collect, accepting a small reallocation. Pick whichever produces less code.

This logic stays INLINE in `Agent::run`. Do NOT extract it to a method or function in this Bead. The seam is visible from its location; extraction lands in Phase 2 when a `ContextCompiler` trait is justified by a second implementation.

The `Agent::run` event loop body otherwise remains the same: send `BlockComplete` for the inbound block, drive the model stream, broadcast `TokenDelta`s, append the `AgentMessage`, send `BlockComplete` + `RunComplete`.

## `src/model/anthropic.rs` rewrite

- The function `block_to_message` is REMOVED entirely. Replace with a private helper that walks `ModelInput`:

```rust
fn model_input_to_anthropic(input: &super::ModelInput) -> (String, Vec<AnthropicMessage>) {
    let mut system = String::new();
    let mut messages = Vec::with_capacity(input.turns.len());
    for turn in &input.turns {
        match turn.role {
            super::Role::System => {
                for part in &turn.content {
                    match part {
                        super::ContentPart::Text(text) => {
                            if !system.is_empty() {
                                system.push_str("\n\n");
                            }
                            system.push_str(text);
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
            super::Role::User | super::Role::Assistant => {
                let role: &'static str = match turn.role {
                    super::Role::User => "user",
                    super::Role::Assistant => "assistant",
                    super::Role::System => unreachable!(),
                };
                let mut text = String::new();
                for part in &turn.content {
                    match part {
                        super::ContentPart::Text(t) => text.push_str(t),
                    }
                }
                messages.push(AnthropicMessage { role, content: text });
            }
        }
    }
    (system, messages)
}
```

The private request type stays roughly the same shape:

```rust
#[derive(serde::Serialize)]
struct AnthropicRequest<'a> {
    model: &'a str,
    max_tokens: u32,
    stream: bool,
    system: &'a str,
    messages: Vec<AnthropicMessage>,
}

#[derive(serde::Serialize)]
struct AnthropicMessage {
    role: &'static str,
    content: String,
}
```

`AnthropicModel::complete` constructs `(system, messages)` from the input, then sends the request as today. The SSE handling and event translation are UNCHANGED.

The `ARModel` impl signature in `anthropic.rs` updates to match the new trait.

